{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486724"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:42:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:42:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"163"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582452"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:43:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:43:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"163"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/163"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.03,0.01,0.89,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"163"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107215"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/163"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"163"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89670"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2228"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"2771"},{"type":"tags","id":"2772"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26538"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39830"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42009"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107215"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of increasing shortness of breath. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes and hypercholesterolaemia, as well as an allergy to penicillin. His regular medications include atorvastatin, paracetamol, and metformin. He does not smoke and lives independently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 140/86 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 90% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals bilateral basal crepitations. Chest X-ray shows bilateral lower zone consolidation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is diagnosed with community-acquired pneumonia and commenced on oral moxifloxacin. The following day, an emergency call is placed for new onset tachycardia. An ECG is taken (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications most likely contributed to the development of this arrhythmia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metformin","Atorvastatin","Paracetamol","Moxifloxacin","Ceftriaxone"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG demonstrates torsade de pointes, a potentially fatal form of polymorphic ventricular tachycardia characterised by a \u0027twisting of points\u0027 appearance. This arrhythmia typically occurs as a complication of QT interval prolongation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMoxifloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E belongs to the fluoroquinolone class of antibiotics, which are well-established to cause QT prolongation and carry a black box warning for this effect. The risk is particularly significant when combined with other risk factors such as electrolyte disturbances (commonly present in acute illness), advanced age, or genetic predisposition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetformin\u003C/strong\u003E is a biguanide antidiabetic medication that does not have any direct cardiac effects and has not been associated with QT prolongation or arrhythmias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtorvastatin\u003C/strong\u003E, while having multiple effects on cardiac health through cholesterol lowering, does not cause QT prolongation or directly precipitate arrhythmias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol\u003C/strong\u003E is a simple analgesic that has no significant cardiac effects when used at therapeutic doses and is not associated with QT prolongation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E, a third-generation cephalosporin antibiotic, has not been associated with QT prolongation or direct cardiac effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of torsade de pointes includes immediate cessation of offending medications, correction of any electrolyte abnormalities (particularly potassium and magnesium), and administration of intravenous magnesium sulphate. In recurrent cases, temporary overdrive pacing or isoprenaline may be required.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Torsade de pointes is a life-threatening ventricular tachycardia characterised by \u0027twisting of points\u0027 on ECG and occurs as a complication of QT prolongation.","Fluoroquinolone antibiotics, particularly moxifloxacin, are strongly associated with QT prolongation and should be used with caution in patients with risk factors.","Multiple factors including medications, electrolyte disturbances, and genetic predisposition can contribute to QT prolongation."],"references":["Roden DM. Drug-Induced Prolongation of the QT Interval. NEJM 2004; 350:1013-22. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMra032426","Vandael E, Vandenberk B, Vandenberghe J, Willems R, Foulon V. Risk factors for QTc-prolongation: systematic review of the evidence. International journal of clinical pharmacy. 2017 Feb;39:16-25. Available at: https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11096-016-0414-2"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89670"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"163"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"739"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/739"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a46162bf-810f-48b8-b7cc-9260abf7680c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a46162bf-810f-48b8-b7cc-9260abf7680c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":549}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89670"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-26T13:57:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-28T12:39:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"163"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107215"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medi